Corruption protocols

Method 1 (as shown last time)
a random value (from 1 to 5 angstrom) is added to all C-alpha cartesian coordinates on one axe (x, y or z)
see here:
Native conformation  http://codepen.io/alogean/live/PbZbPK
Decoy conformation http://codepen.io/alogean/live/rWxMoQ
a variation could be to do the same but this time chosing also randomly the dimensions

Method 2
use a the PDBviewer to modify the structure
rule set 1
select in the middle of each loop an amino acid
rotate the dihedral angle of on increment right
repeat it for each loop
rule set 2
select in the middle of each loop an amino acid
rotate the dihedral angle of one increment right
repeat it for the next loop but this turn left (alternate right left)
rule set 3
select in the middle of each loop an amino acid
rotate the dihedral angle of two increment right
repeat it for the next loop
rule set 4
as 2 but with 2 increment
rule set 5
as for 1 but only loops that are bigger than 10 aa
rule set 6
select only loop that are bigger as 10 aa and select then 2 amino acid in the loop 

Method 3
Threading method : take an other protein with the same length, and mutate all amino acid to the original one


    





About conformation that are "physicaly impossibles"
The best way to describe this is to use probability and potential energy: at room temperature, in water there are conformations that are "possibles" but so high in energy that the probability to find them is extremelly low. So "physicaly impossible" should be replaced by "very unlikelly" because so high in energy.  

Protein selection
There are many ways to classify proteins: 
by function
by size
by shape
by complexity
...
see here http://mm.rcsb.org/
    
Existing Decoy Dets 
Titan High resolution decoy set
http://titan.princeton.edu/2010-10-11/Decoys/
Tasser Set II
structurally non-redundant set of protein structures and decoys derived with the program TASSER.
http://zhanglab.ccmb.med.umich.edu/decoys/
Decoy sets from the Decoys ‘R’ us repository 
http://dd.compbio.washington.edu
Different decoy Rosetta-based decoy sets
http://depts.washington.edu/bakerpg/decoys/
Collection of models from the successive CASP5 to CASP9 experiments
http://predictioncenter.org
The Stage_1 and Stage_2 decoy sets used in the CASP10 quality assessment category
http://predictioncenter.org

